<div id="review_3351491826" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3351491826" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35467021-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578711589p2/35467021.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3351491826?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/35467021-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/21419116-black-elk-speaks">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3351491826" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8120895174746406678">Black Elk lived an unparalleled life, but I have a hard time writing a review knowing the embellishments Neihardt made to Black Elk&apos;s narrative and the criticisms of such changes were to make the story more accessible and marketable to a white audience. Just analyzing what is in the book, Black Elk Speaks follows an audio-biographical account of his life from childhood through Wounded Knee as a warrior and holy man. Black Elk is Oglala, but the book also dives into the relations with other Lakot</span>
  <span id="freeText8120895174746406678" style="display:none">Black Elk lived an unparalleled life, but I have a hard time writing a review knowing the embellishments Neihardt made to Black Elk's narrative and the criticisms of such changes were to make the story more accessible and marketable to a white audience. Just analyzing what is in the book, Black Elk Speaks follows an audio-biographical account of his life from childhood through Wounded Knee as a warrior and holy man. Black Elk is Oglala, but the book also dives into the relations with other Lakota peoples like the Hunkpapa and Minneconjou. The book begins with Black Elk's vision as a child and progresses through the Battle of Little Big Horn, his time with Buffalo Bill's Wild West European tour, and ends following Wounded Knee. I found the entire text quite fascinating, but wished the book dove into Black Elk's life beyond Wounded Knee, especially given the speculations around his conversion to Christianity in the early twentieth century. Overall it was a good read, but I would advise readers not to rely on this book solely for their education on Black Elk and the Lakota peoples.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8120895174746406678" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

